		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					What is a Mage to YOU!
				</h2>
				

						
							
							
							
						
						
				<div class="content ">
					<div id="post_message_1344846">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Not in the context of vanguard specifically, but considering all of your gaming experience, what roles constitute what a mage should be able to do? <br />
<br />
<br />
What I really, REALLY would love to know is if I have missed any part of being a &quot;caster,&quot; I've tried to find any role that pertains to all spell casters. <br />
<br />
If you could answer below with the following, I would really love to hear your feedback: <br />
<br />
1.) What you personally think are the total roles that you have ever seen for a Mage in general (note, not a mage specifically in the context of a given game, such as eq1, but in all games you have come across, the general themes) <br />
<br />
2.) Which is your personal favorite? Can you give an example of a class from a specific game that has this play style? <br />
<br />
3.) After reading my information provided below, do you like the current list of my 5 Paths? What is missing in your opinion? (note, keep in mind that you can mix and match your Paths, so many classes in other games can essentially be recreated by combining them) <br />
<br />
Also note that the &quot;elementalist&quot; type mage is actually part of the Druid class as their Summoner, so I haven't left out the good old eq1 magician! <br />
<br />
4.) Keep in mind that the list below is only of the &quot;Mages,&quot; while the Druid and Priests also have a similar list, so I have not forgotten about lightning-tossing druids or shadow calling priests as heavy damage dealers as well! Priests and Druids will have a Primary dps, Secondary dps, Summoner, Healer, and their own class specific Path as well  <br />
<br />
<br />
First, a few things to understand. <br />
<br />
<br />
First, the 5 Paths are part of the Class. Think of the Paths as the EQ2 AA's, if each AA line was a complete class, and the &quot;Class&quot; with the 5 AA Paths was just a tittle consolidating them all. They are not really classes themselves, as you can switch between them in mid combat, so they are technically components of the Class, though they are designed well enough to in all practical cases be considered classes in their own rite, rather than simple specializations. You only have so many points you can devote to advancing the 5 Paths, so choosing how strong you wish to be in each individually is important. You can switch between each Path in mid combat, which takes roughly 2 seconds, as you change out your foci and your UI changes to be appropriate for your current Path. You could be a top of the line damage dealer, and then switch over to a top of the line healer, for example. Or, you could go from a great damage dealer role to a damage enabler to help cut off a foe's defenses. Being flexible in combat is crucial, because foes can and WILL change role in combat as well depending on their situation, so being a master of one Role while acceptable in a second might not always be the best method. <br />
<br />
A second thing thats important to know about my design is that there are two health bars: Health and Resilience. Physical damage effects Health, while magical damage effects Resilience. The third bar is Life, which is attacked after Health or Resilience has been depleted. If out of Health, Physical attacks hurt life, if out of Resilience, magical attacks hurt Life. Certain classes also have &quot;finishing moves&quot; that deal extreme damage when a foe is reduced to their Life bar, but they are difficult to execute and easily interrupted. Keep in mind about these distinctions when reading about the following: <br />
<br />
So, a Telekinetic Blast from an Enchanter is physical, while a Mental Blast would be magical. A ethereal energy sword slice from a Spellweaver is Magic damage, while controlling their blade from a distance to strike the foe would be Physical. A necromancer causing a foe's flesh to rot is Physical, while sucking the life force from their body is Magical. A psionicist causing a time rift, displacing the foes body to cause injury, is Physical. A Bloodmage causing a lesion in the foes flesh is Physical. <br />
<br />
Some foes will require different damage based on what is their weakest point, either magical or physical, so having the ability to switch between the 5 Paths during combat will be highly important, but ill skip the details.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>General Roles for all 3 Caster Classes: </b><br />
<br />
<br />
Primary DPS (sorcerer, Wizard, WOW mage), also they generally deal much more Magic than Physical damage. Has the best Finishing capabilities. <br />
<br />
Secondary DPS (necromancer, damage-enhancers / defense lowering, good over-time dps) they generally do much more Physical than Magical damage. Second best finishing capabilities. <br />
<br />
Healer (Bloodmage, traditional &quot;clerics&quot; and druids) - This is required due to the design of my game, as each of my 3 caster classes has a Healer role in it. <br />
<br />
Summoners (eq1 or 2 mages, necromancers, wow warlock ect..) They generally do even in terms of Magical and Physical damage. <br />
<br />
Lastly... <br />
<br />
The &quot;Odd Ball 5th section&quot;, which is specific for each Class, so there is no generic description that covers all three Class's role here. <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
The following descriptions specifically applies to the Mage caster class's Paths. The Druid and Priest casters have their own set of 5 Paths as well, but they are not included in this post. <br />
<br />
<br />
So far, what I have in my design for the Mage class is: <br />
<br />
<font size="5">Mage Class: </font><br />
<br />
<b>Spellweaver</b>: the primary dps <br />
<br />
Uses a Wind-blade as their casting focus, and several of their spells involve sword swinging animations. Can also project their blade forward at a range to inflict physical damage as well. <br />
<br />
They have powerful magic damage capability with mild physical damage capability. <br />
<br />
Heavy spell damage along with heavy spell damage, they will have a spell-gathering system called Channeling which is based on Evocation, Conjuration, Alteration, and Restoration. The more spells of each school cast around them, the more powerful certain aspects of the Spellweaver become, and the more abilities they gain access to. <br />
<br />
<b>Necromancer</b>: the secondary dps <br />
<br />
Uses a Scythe as their casting focus, they have strong physical damage over time capability, moderate magical direct damage, and powerful damage enhancement via powerful debuffing, also has a corpse manipulation mechanic that uses corpses for several spells. <br />
<br />
<b>Bloodmage</b>: the healer <br />
<br />
Arcane-related Healing, they use a Ritual Dagger as their casting focus, almost identical to the Bloodmage of Vanguard, but with a stronger focus on manipulating damage and health through blood unions, life tapping is a major focus, and imparting their health to others. <br />
<br />
Has moderate physical damage, no magic damage, and great healing potential. <br />
<br />
<b>Enchanter</b>: the summoner <br />
<br />
Summoning mentally projected pets and minions mixed in with limited crowd control and ally enhancements. <br />
<br />
Can have moderate magical and physical damage capability, moderate tanking capability and moderate healing capability, all depending on the pets being utilized along with their personal spells. <br />
<br />
<br />
The final Path of the Mage class is the class's unique Path, which the other two caster Classes, the Priest and the Druid, do not have a similar role: <br />
<br />
<b>Psionicist</b>: The odd-ball class specific role. <br />
<br />
Manipulating time and space to CC multiple foes, hands down the best CC in the game, highly capable of enhancing allies casting time / execution time (how long it takes to 'cast' a melee ability), as well as slowing foe's casting / execution time. <br />
<br />
Best CC capability in the game, Moderate physical damage, no magic damage. Has 2 special meters that fill up as time elapses, one for Spatial magic and the other for Temporal magic, each used to fuel specific spells.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
