				</div>
				<div class="message"> Good feedback, thanks!<br />
<br />
So, if you had a class with the ability to switch between damage types, cast with subtlety if needed, and unleash the beast when desired, with low defensive capability, you would be satisfied right?</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Pretty much yes. VG casters tend to be pretty much 1 dimensional.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>jhorry</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=9b2f657e51095d52a834430905234931&amp;p=1345698#post1345698" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Does it have to be elemental damage, or would other types work as well?</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Elemental is a typical method. whether you use the typical european earth/air/fire/water, the oriental wood/metal, or create your own, they could best be used in some fashion of the following;<br />
<br />
ex 1: Mob is Fire based, fire spells do little or no damage, maybe even heal. All non-Fire damage works as normal.<br />
<br />
ex 2: Use an elemental 'wheel' such that  earth &gt; air &gt; fire &gt; water &gt; earth.  An Earth based target would be vulnerable to air, immune to earth, and say patially resistant to fire and water.<br />
<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>jhorry</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=9b2f657e51095d52a834430905234931&amp;p=1345698#post1345698" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Generally, switching between different elements wont be a huge boon, but on some foes you will get the bonuses.<br />
<br />
The biggest difference will be using Physical or Magical damage spells though, as these each attack different health bars.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>The exact mechanism can be as you set it, so long as the player isn't stuck in the 1,2,3,1,2,3,1,2,3,1,2,3.... trap. I want a mechanism that is flexible enough to allow me a reason to use more than just 3 of the 50 spells in my grimoire.<br />
<br />
There needs to be something unique to make a spell/skill viable. Players WILL find the most efficient and use that exclusively. If all things operate the same then even a 0.01% advantage will determine what gets used. Would you want the 12.1 DPS sword, OR the 12.2 DPS sword?!? Not a lot of difference, but players will take the 12.2 one 999 out of 1000.<br />
<br />
If spell A, spell B and spell C all do the same damage damage for the same costs either drop 2 of the spells from the list or give the player a true and solid reason to use one over another.
						</blockquote>
