		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: What is a Mage to YOU!
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1347793">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Probably best if I link one of my more complete Paths, the Duskbringer, for an example of how I have the abilities designed so far.<br />
<br />
What would be the easiest way to send you a 2007 word document? Do you have any instant messengers that allow sending, or would email be easier?<br />
<br />
I would just copy and paste it on here but its several pages long and wouldnt keep the formating.<br />
<br />
EDIT:<br />
<br />
As a short list:<br />
<br />
The Duskbringer's unique mechanic is that they can split their soul into shadow beings, allowing them to cast multiple spells at once or enhance the potency of their normal spells, or even perform rituals that consume their shadow souls.<br />
<br />
The cost of creating a shadow soul varies depending on the Tier of the Duskbringer, but this damage penalty lessens as you get higher.<br />
<br />
Starts at 60%, then raises to 65, 70, 75, and finally ends at 80% damage capacity for using any soul shades. In other words, forming even one soul shade lowers your personal damage. Summoning multiples will not lower your personal damage further.<br />
<br />
Each soul shade also takes 20% of the Duskbringer's health and resilience, meaning they compromise their safety a bit by partitioning their soul.<br />
<br />
If a soul shade should die in combat, the Duskbringer still has the 20% less health penalty for 1 minute, and cannot summon a new Soul shard to replace the lost one, as its spot is still considered &quot;filled&quot; due to the self-imposed debuff. This means that if a Tier 3 Duskbringer has 3 Soul shards, and all three die, and then he still has his reduced health which is down to 40%, and his 70% damage restriction, until the 1 minute timer wears off for each slain Soul Shard. The timers are separate, not cumulative.<br />
<br />
In other words, you have to be cautious if you are summoning a lot of Soul Shards at once, or else you could end up seriously crippled for a time period.<br />
<br />
Duskbringer's single target damage spells are as follows:<br />
<br />
Shadow Bolt - basic Dark Resilience Damage nuke, its damage improves with each Soul Shade you have out, and the Soul Shades will also cast their own bolt in tandem with your own.<br />
<br />
Obsidian Strike - basic Health damage nuke, 1 second casting time 10 second reuse timer, and has a chance to interrupt the foe's current action, your Soul Shades cast it in tandem with you. 200% health damage.<br />
<br />
Clinging Darkness - basic damage over time + 60% ground snare over 30 seconds, deals 300% resilience damage total.<br />
<br />
Agony of the Void - powerful single target dot that deals 600% resilience damage over 30 seconds with a 5 second casting time. The casting time is reduced by .75 and the duration by 4 seconds with each Soul Shade active. So, if you had 4 Soul Shades, that would lower the casting time to 2 seconds, and the duration to 14 seconds, which really ups its dps.<br />
<br />
Raven's Barrage - assaults your foes with dark obsidian ravens that impede aerial movement, slowing flight speed by 60% and dealing 300% damage over 30 seconds<br />
<br />
Beam of Darkness - requires caster to focus for 5 seconds, and directs a beam of dark energy at the targeted foe, any foes in this path receive 100% resilience damage every second. Soul Shades will cast in tandem, and with each Soul Shade, the duration of the beam is lowered by .5 (aka it damages faster) this spell has a 45 second reuse timer.<br />
<br />
Obsidian Rend - deals massive health damage by raking the for with an obsidian claw, dealing 400% health damage instantly, with a 30 second reuse. Has a base cast of 3 seconds, reuse of 30, but each soul shade active lowers the cast by .5, and the reuse timer by 3.<br />
<br />
Dark Rift - the lure spell for any foe that is highly resistant to your other attempts, great for bypassing defenses and attacking health and resilience simultaneously. Deals 125% Health and Resilience damage, but has a 4 second casting time. Each Soul shade active adds +25% damage to this attack.<br />
<br />
Anathema - A finishing attack that can only be used when the foe's Resilience is depleted, it is a deadly shadow curse that attempts to banish the soul of your target to the Void, dealing 1000% Life damage. 4 second casting time, easily interrupted and counter spelled. 1 minute reuse timer, but a deadly ability if your group can help you land it.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Those are the basic single target damage spells of this primary damage class.<br />
<br />
There are at least 3 or 4 AOE spells I didnt mention, several abilities involving using the Soul Shades as catalysts for powerful spells, and some abilities for temporary defense.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
So, depending on your foe, you need to either focus on attacking his Health with the physical spells, or his Resilience, with the magical spells.<br />
<br />
If he is highly defensive, then using Dark Void to bypass his defense would be a good idea, or let someone else (a secondary dps) temporarily cripple his defenses then you strike with a heavy blow.<br />
<br />
Above all else, as a Primary dps class, you are the only class that has Finishing blows that can quickly finish off the Life bar after Resilience has been broken through, so spotting this opportunity and getting your allies to protect you so you can complete the spell is crucial.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
